<dt><strong>copy</strong><span class=3D"classifier">bool, default=3DTrue</s=
pan></dt><dd><p>If False, data passed to fit are overwritten and running
fit(X).transform(X) will not yield the expected results,
use fit_transform(X) instead.</p>
</dd>
<dt><strong>whiten</strong><span class=3D"classifier">bool, default=3DFalse=
</span></dt><dd><p>When True (False by default) the <code class=3D"docutils=
 literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">components_</span></code> vectors=
 are multiplied
by the square root of n_samples and then divided by the singular values
to ensure uncorrelated outputs with unit component-wise variances.</p>
<p>Whitening will remove some information from the transformed signal
(the relative variance scales of the components) but can sometime
improve the predictive accuracy of the downstream estimators by
making their data respect some hard-wired assumptions.</p>
</dd>
<dt><strong>svd_solver</strong><span class=3D"classifier">{=E2=80=98auto=E2=
=80=99, =E2=80=98full=E2=80=99, =E2=80=98covariance_eigh=E2=80=99, =E2=80=
=98arpack=E2=80=99, =E2=80=98randomized=E2=80=99},            default=3D=E2=
=80=99auto=E2=80=99</span></dt><dd><dl class=3D"simple">
<dt>=E2=80=9Cauto=E2=80=9D :</dt><dd><p>The solver is selected by a default=
 =E2=80=98auto=E2=80=99 policy is based on <code class=3D"docutils literal =
notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">X.shape</span></code> and
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">n_componen=
ts</span></code>: if the input data has fewer than 1000 features and
more than 10 times as many samples, then the =E2=80=9Ccovariance_eigh=E2=80=
=9D
solver is used. Otherwise, if the input data is larger than 500x500
and the number of components to extract is lower than 80% of the
smallest dimension of the data, then the more efficient
=E2=80=9Crandomized=E2=80=9D method is selected. Otherwise the exact =E2=80=
=9Cfull=E2=80=9D SVD is
computed and optionally truncated afterwards.</p>
</dd>
<dt>=E2=80=9Cfull=E2=80=9D :</dt><dd><p>Run exact full SVD calling the stan=
dard LAPACK solver via
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">scipy.lina=
lg.svd</span></code> and select the components by postprocessing</p>
</dd>
<dt>=E2=80=9Ccovariance_eigh=E2=80=9D :</dt><dd><p>Precompute the covarianc=
e matrix (on centered data), run a
classical eigenvalue decomposition on the covariance matrix
typically using LAPACK and select the components by postprocessing.
This solver is very efficient for n_samples &gt;&gt; n_features and small
n_features. It is, however, not tractable otherwise for large
n_features (large memory footprint required to materialize the
covariance matrix). Also note that compared to the =E2=80=9Cfull=E2=80=9D s=
olver,
this solver effectively doubles the condition number and is
therefore less numerical stable (e.g. on input data with a large
range of singular values).</p>
</dd>
<dt>=E2=80=9Carpack=E2=80=9D :</dt><dd><p>Run SVD truncated to <code class=
=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">n_components</span></=
code> calling ARPACK solver via
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">scipy.spar=
se.linalg.svds</span></code>. It requires strictly
<code class=3D"docutils literal notranslate"><span class=3D"pre">0</span> <=
span class=3D"pre">&lt;</span> <span class=3D"pre">n_components</span> <spa=
n class=3D"pre">&lt;</span> <span class=3D"pre">min(X.shape)</span></code><=
/p>
</dd>
<dt>=E2=80=9Crandomized=E2=80=9D :</dt><dd><p>Run randomized SVD by the met=
hod of Halko et al.</p>
</dd>
</dl>
<div class=3D"versionadded">
